SIMPLE: saturnian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saturnian
<hw>Sa*tur"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Saturnius</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Roman Myth.)</fld>
<def>Of or pertaining to Saturn, whose age or reign, from the mildness
and wisdom of his government, is called the <xex>golden
age</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Resembling the golden age; distinguished for
peacefulness, happiness, contentment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Augustus, born to bring <qex>Saturnian</qex> times.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the planet
Saturn; <as>as, the <ex>Saturnian</ex> year</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Saturnian verse</b></col> <fld>(Pros.)</fld>, <cd>a meter
employed by early Roman satirists, consisting of three iambics and an
extra syllable followed by three trochees, as in the line: -- Th⟦ecr⟧
qu⟦emac⟧en | w⟦acr⟧s ⟦imac⟧n | th⟦ecr⟧ k⟦imac⟧tch | ⟦ecr⟧n \'d8
⟦emac⟧at⟦icr⟧ng | br⟦emac⟧ad ⟦acr⟧nd | h⟦omac⟧n⟦ecr⟧y. </cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saturnian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Saturnian
<hw>Sa*tur"ni*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of
numerous species of large handsome moths belonging to
<gen>Saturnia</gen> and allied genera. The luna moth, polyphemus, and
promethea, are examples. They belong to the Silkworn family, and some
are raised for their silk. See <er>Polyphemus</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saturnicentric</ent>⟦br⟧
